            <corr>e</corr>
          </choice> datta<supplied reason="omitted">M</supplied><unclear>|</unclear> yato smat-santakāḥ sarvv<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice>ddhyakṣa-niyoga-
<lb n="10"/>niyuktāḥ Ājñā-<space type="binding-hole"/>sañcāri-kula-putrādhikr̥tāḥ bhaṭāś chātrāś ca vi<choice>
            <sic>ṣr̥</sic>
            <corr>śru</corr>
          </choice>ta-pūrvvayājñ<supplied reason="omitted">ay</supplied>ājñā<lb break="no" n="11"/>payitavyā<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied><!-- 
The punctuation after grāma in l7 is a blotch on the rubbing; proably a dash originally. 
--><!-- 
I retain Mirashi's reading of ṣadviṣati in l8. He suggests the emendation ṣaḍviṁśati (and likewise for ṣadviśaka in IN00159:7). I believe we could very well read ṣaḍ both here and in IN00159; I don't expect ḍ to look conspicuously different from d in this script; compare ṣoḍaśy (read as such by Mirashi) in IN00158:1. 
--><!-- 
The punctuation in l8 is a double horizontal dash. 
--><!-- 
Mirashi prints taittiriya in l9 with a single t in CII5; his transliteration is correctly tti in EI24. 
--><!-- 
There is a very small space after taittiriya. 
--></p>
        <p>viditam astu vaḥ yath<choice>
            <sic>ai</sic>
            <corr>e</corr>
          </choice>hāsmābhir ātmano dharmmāyur-bbala vijay<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ai</corr>
          </choice>śvaryya-vivr̥ddhaye<surplus>|</surplus> ihā<lb break="no" n="12"/>mutra-hitārttham ātmānugrah<choice>
            <sic>a</sic>
            <corr>ā</corr>
          </choice>ya vaij<choice>
            <sic>jai</sic>
            <corr>jayi</corr>
          </choice>ke dharmma-sthāne Apūrvva-dat<supplied reason="omitted">t</supplied>yā Udaka-pūrvvam atisr̥ṣṭaḥ<!-- 
The superfluous punctuation in l11 is a dash close to baseline height. 
--><!-- 
For ihā in l11, Mirashi prints iha in CII5; his text is correctly ihā in EI24. 
--><!-- 
As Mirashi points out in both EI and CII, atisr̥ṣṭaḥ in l12 does not agree with grāmadvayam above. He only proposes a correction to atisr̥ṣṭam, but neglects to mention that this may in fact be circumstantial evidence that this plate is a forgery. (However, what he reads as a visarga may in fact be punctuation, and then we only have to supply a missing anusvāra.) 
--></p>
